#import "../image_list/6_Leaves_images.typ": images
#set text(font: "Arial")
#set page(numbering: "1", number-align: center)

#align(center, text(2em, weight: "bold")[Leaves])

= Concepts

- *Foliage leaves* are large, flat, green structures involved in photosynthesis.
- Natural selection has produced numerous types of leaves for protection (*bud scales*, *spines*), support (*tendrils*), storage (fleshy leaves), and nitrogen procurement (insect traps).
- Leaves are typically flat and thin for maximum absorption of light and #ce("CO_2").
- Most leaf tissues are alive and differentiated into chlorophyll-rich chlorenchyma.
- Leaves typically live for only several months and contain only primary tissues; secondary production of wood and bark is rare.

= External Structure of Foliage Leaves

- Functions of foliage leaves:
  - Photosynthesis: absorb #ce("CO_2") and convert it to carbohydrate using light energy.
  - Water conservation: must not lose excessive water.
  - Protection: against fungi, bacteria, epifoliar algae, and herbivores.
- *Leaf blade* (or *lamina*): the flat, light-harvesting portion.
  - *Dorsal surface* (abaxial): lower side, often with protruding veins.
  - *Ventral surface* (adaxial): upper side, usually smooth.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-1").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-1").caption
  )
- *Petiole*: the stalk that holds the blade out into the light, preventing self-shading.
  - Allows blade flutter to cool the leaf and bring fresh air (replenishing #ce("CO_2")).
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-2").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-2").caption
  )
  #figure(
    image(images.at("table-6-1").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("table-6-1").caption
  )
- *Sessile leaf*: lacks a petiole; common in small or long narrow leaves where self-shading is not a problem (e.g., _Aeonium_).
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-3").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-3").caption
  )
- *Sheathing leaf base*: leaf base wraps around the stem; common in monocots (grasses, lilies, etc.).
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-4").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-4").caption
  )
- Broad leaves in monocots: some have petiole-like structures (e.g., _Maranta_), but may be modified laminas.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-5").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-5").caption
  )
- *Simple leaf*: blade consists of just one part.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-6").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-6").caption
  )
- *Compound leaf*: blade divided into several individual parts called *leaflets*.
  - *Petiolule*: stalk attaching a leaflet to the *rachis* (extension of the petiole).
  - *Palmately compound*: all leaflets attached at the same point.
  - *Pinnately compound*: leaflets attached individually along the rachis.
  - Advantages: prevents tearing by wind, increases turbulence (bringing in #ce("CO_2")), and acts as a barrier to pathogens.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-7").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-7").caption
  )
- *Doubly compound leaf*: leaflets themselves are compound (e.g., _Mimosa_).
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-8").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-8").caption
  )
- *Heterophylly*: different leaf forms on the same plant (e.g., aquatic vs aerial leaves in _Myriophyllum_).
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-9").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-9").caption
  )
- *Economic importance and defense*:
  - Leaves provide food (cabbage, lettuce) and flavorings (herbs, spices).
  - Flavors often due to antiherbivore chemicals (e.g., alkaloids like nicotine in tobacco).
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-b6-1").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-b6-1").caption
  )
- Leaf shapes vary widely and are used for identification.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-10").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-10").caption
  )
- *Heteroblasty*: juvenile leaves differ from adult leaves (e.g., beans, ivy).
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-11").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-11").caption
  )
- Leaf margins: can be entire, toothed, lobed, etc.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-12").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-12").caption
  )
- Venation patterns:
  - *Reticulate venation*: netted pattern, common in basal angiosperms and eudicots.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-13").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-13").caption
  )
  - *Leaf clearings*: reveal high density of veins; every cell is close to a vein.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-14").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-14").caption
  )
  - *Parallel venation*: larger veins run side by side, common in monocots.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-15").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-15").caption
  )
  - Cross-veins: fine transverse veins allow conduction if longitudinal veins are broken.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-16").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-16").caption
  )
- *Abscission zone*: oriented perpendicular to the petiole at the leaf base.
  - Cells release enzymes to weaken walls, allowing leaf to fall.
  - *Leaf scar*: protective corky tissue formed across the wound.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-17").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-17").caption
  )
- Non-abscising leaves: dead leaves persist (e.g., Joshua tree), forming a protective skirt.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-18").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-18").caption
  )

= Internal Structure of Foliage Leaves

== Epidermis

- *Transpiration*: water loss through the epidermis.
- Structure: flat, tabular cells, guard cells (stomata), and trichomes.
- Stomata distribution: usually more abundant on the lower epidermis to minimize water loss (avoiding convection currents on the heated upper surface).
  #figure(
    image(images.at("table-6-2").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("table-6-2").caption
  )
- Stomatal crypts: sunken cavities with trichomes (e.g., oleander) to trap moist air and reduce water loss.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-19").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-19").caption
  )
- *Trichomes*:
  - Provide shade (deflect sunlight).
  - Prevent rapid air movement (slow water loss).
  - Deter insects (walking difficulty, stinging compounds).
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-20").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-20").caption
  )
- Cuticle and wax: retain water and prevent fungal digestion.

== Mesophyll

- *Mesophyll*: ground tissues interior to the epidermis.
- *Palisade parenchyma* (palisade mesophyll):
  - Usually along the upper surface.
  - Main photosynthetic tissue.
  - Cells separated slightly for maximum surface area for #ce("CO_2") absorption.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-21").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-21").caption
  )
- Surface area: slight separation of cells increases area for #ce("CO_2") absorption.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-22").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-22").caption
  )
- Thickness: can be multiple layers in high light (e.g., holly).
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-23").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-23").caption
  )
- *Spongy mesophyll*:
  - Located in the lower portion.
  - Open, loose aerenchyma permitting rapid #ce("CO_2") diffusion.
- Some plants have palisade parenchyma on both sides (e.g., vertical leaves).
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-24").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-24").caption
  )

== Vascular Tissues

- *Midrib* (midvein) and *lateral veins*: contain primary xylem (upper) and primary phloem (lower).
- *Bundle sheath*: fiber sheath around vascular tissues for support and protection.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-25").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-25").caption
  )
- *Bundle sheath extension*: fibers extending to epidermis, providing support and conducting water to mesophyll.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-26").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-26").caption
  )
- *Minor veins*: sites of material exchange; large surface area in contact with mesophyll; no fibers.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-27").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-27").caption
  )
- *Leaf Structure Review* (Box 6-2):
  - Palisade parenchyma: cylindrical, not closely packed.
  - Veins: network below palisade.
  - Spongy mesophyll: extensive air space.
  - Lower epidermis: abundant stomata.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-b6-2").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-b6-2").caption
  )

== Petiole

- Transition between stem and lamina.
- *Petiole vascularization*: vascular bundles (leaf traces) branch from stem and enter petiole; patterns vary (ring, plate, etc.).
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-28").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-28").caption
  )
- *Stipules*: small flaps of tissue at the petiole base; may protect the shoot apical meristem.

= Initiation and Development of Leaves

== Basal Angiosperms and Eudicots

- *Leaf primordium*: protrusion from the shoot apical meristem.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-29").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-29").caption
  )
- Development:
  - Primordium grows upward as a narrow cone.
  - Midrib establishes thickness.
  - Marginal meristems initiate the lamina (wings).
  - In compound leaves, leaflet primordia are initiated.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-30").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-30").caption
  )
- Cellular activity: cells are small, cytoplasmic, dividing; veins differentiate.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-31").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-31").caption
  )
- Expansion:
  - In perennials, leaves may be initiated in autumn and expand in spring.
  - Expansion involves water absorption and cell swelling.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-32").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-32").caption
  )
- Vulnerability: young leaves lack sclerenchyma and are vulnerable to insects (e.g., aphids).
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-33").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-33").caption
  )

== Monocots

- Leaf primordium encircles the shoot apical meristem to form a sheathing leaf base.
- Lamina grows from a basal meristem (intercalary meristem) at the top of the sheath.
- Allows continuous growth (e.g., grasses) even if the tip is removed.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-34").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-34").caption
  )
- *Photosynthesis Without Leaves* (Box 6-3):
  - *Photosynthetic bark*: green bark with chlorophyll (e.g., palo verde); "recycling" photosynthesis.
  - *Photosynthetic cortex*: common in young stems and stem succulents (cacti).
  - *Stem succulents*: store water, have stomata in stem epidermis, and cortical bundles.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-b6-3").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-b6-3").caption
  )

= Morphology and Anatomy of Other Leaf Types

== Succulent Leaves

- Adapted for water storage in desert habitats.
- Thick and fleshy with reduced surface-to-volume ratio.
- Mesophyll has few air spaces (reduces water loss, increases transparency).
- Examples: Crassulaceae, _Lithops_.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-35").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-35").caption
  )
- *Window leaves*: translucent tips conduct light to subterranean chlorenchyma (e.g., _Lithops_).
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-36").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-36").caption
  )

== Sclerophyllous Foliage Leaves

- *Sclerophylls*: tough, hard leaves with abundant sclerenchyma (fibers).
- Perennial leaves (2+ years).
- Resistant to animals, fungi, freezing, and UV light.
- Examples: barberry, holly, _Yucca_.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-37").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-37").caption
  )
- Structure: thick cuticle, thick-walled epidermis, fiber bundles, fiber sheaths.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-38").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-38").caption
  )

== Leaves of Conifers

- Mostly sclerophylls with thick cuticle and thick-walled epidermis/hypodermis.
- Simple leaves: needles (pine, fir) or scales (juniper, cypress).
- Perennial (evergreen).
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-39").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-39").caption
  )
- Scale leaves: small, flat, shield-like (e.g., _Araucaria_).
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-40").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-40").caption
  )
- Needle structure: round in section, resin canals, sunken stomata.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-41").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-41").caption
  )

== Bud Scales

- Modified leaves protecting dormant shoot apical meristems.
- Small, tough, waxy, often corky; short or absent petiole.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-42").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-42").caption
  )

== Spines

- Modified leaves of axillary buds (e.g., cacti).
- Protective function; no blade; mesophyll consists of fibers.
- Photosynthesis carried out by stem cortex.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-43").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-43").caption
  )

== Tendrils

- Modified leaves for support (e.g., peas).
- Grow indefinitely; sense contact and coil around objects.
- No lamina.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-44").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-44").caption
  )

== Leaves with Kranz Anatomy

- Occur in C4 plants.
- Lack distinct palisade/spongy mesophyll.
- Prominent bundle sheaths with large chlorophyllous cells surrounded by a ring of mesophyll cells.

== Insect Traps

- Adapted for nitrogen-poor habitats.
- Active traps (move): Venus' flytrap, sundew.
- Passive traps (no movement): pitcher plants.
- Digest insects to obtain nitrogen.
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-6-45").path, width: 50%),
    caption: images.at("figure-6-45").caption
  )
